10/12/2003
TIRANA, Albania -- A two-day conference of the Southeast Europe Police Chiefs Association (SEPCA) started in Tirana on Tuesday (9 December).
The event featured the heads of police from seven Southeastern European countries -- Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Bulgaria, Croatia, Macedonia, Romania and Serbia-Montenegro.
Discussions focused on ways to improve regional co-operation in organised crime fighting, training and education of police staff, as well as security and judicial reforms.
In other news, the Fourth Regional Forum of Southeastern European Ministers of Justice and Interior begins Wednesday in Sofia.
The conference would focus on issues related to children trafficking victims' protection.
(Albanian Radio, BBC - 09/12/03)
